# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aftermarket-merchandise
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] In the moment, aftermarket goods mainly include products and services for replacement parts, upgrade, maintenance and enhancement.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] There are two essential elements of the aftermarket: installed base and vendor lock-in effect.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] A certain level of installed base of original equipment customers is necessary for the sufficient demand of aftermarket products.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] Therefore, significant installed base normally makes aftermarket profitable as an established installed base is likely to consume the aftermarket products repeatedly over the lifespan of their durable goods.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] Lock-in effect or installed-base opportunism refers to the situation where the customers can only purchase the aftermarket goods produced by original equipment manufacturer.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] These two essentials, installed base and lock-in effect, make aftermarket less volatile relative to primary market and therefore more likely to be profitable.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] The most well-known aftermarket strategy model is "Gillette's razor and blades business model" also known as "freebie marketing" whereby a product is largely discounted or even free as a loss leader in order to increase the sales of its complementary goods.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] Often the durable goods are offered at a low price (or even below marginal cost) in order to attract new customers amid competitive primary markets and the loss from the primary market will be rebated by the profits from consumables in aftermarket.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] In this case, an established installed base is essential to ensure sustainable business practice.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] Tying or bundling of aftermarket products with original equipment also could be the strategies for aftermarket.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] There have been a significant number of economic literature discussing about the aftermarket monopolisation after US Supreme Court's 1992 decision in the case *Eastman Kodak Company v.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] The key issue of the debate is whether the monopolisation in the aftermarket harms customers and social welfare.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] In addition, the Chicago school argues that aftermarket monopolization enables manufacturers to afford investments into quality improvement of their original equipment; consumers may benefit from quality primary goods for lower price and overall economic efficiency therefore increases.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] In addition, the post-Chicago school economists argue that the primary market where the investments costs in original equipment are largely subsidized by the profits from its monopolized aftermarket tend to be anti-competitive as entry into a market will be difficult without installed base.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] Although Chicago school economists assumes that theoretically consumers are farsighted and rational, the results of a number of empirical economic literature insist that consumers are in many cases highly myopic towards the sophisticated choices.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] Thus, now there is consensus that aftermarket monopolization has potential harms even when consumers are fully informed about the whole lifecycle costs with the competitive primary market.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/aftermarket-merchandise] Following is a list of factors making aftermarket monopolization more harmful.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The **Chicago school of economics** is a neoclassical school of economic thought associated with the work of the faculty at the University of Chicago, some of whom have constructed and popularized its principles.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Milton Friedman and George Stigler are considered the leading scholars of the Chicago school.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Chicago macroeconomic theory rejected Keynesianism in favor of monetarism until the mid-1970s, when it turned to new classical macroeconomics heavily based on the concept of rational expectations.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The freshwater–saltwater distinction is largely antiquated today, as the two traditions have heavily incorporated ideas from each other.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Specifically, new Keynesian economics was developed as a response to new classical economics, electing to incorporate the insight of rational expectations without giving up the traditional Keynesian focus on imperfect competition and sticky wages.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Chicago economists have also left their intellectual influence in other fields, notably in pioneering public choice theory and law and economics, which have led to revolutionary changes in the study of political science and law.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Other economists affiliated with Chicago have made their impact in fields as diverse as social economics and economic history.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] As of 2025, the University of Chicago Economics department, considered one of the world's foremost economics departments, has been awarded 15 Nobel Memorial Prizes in Economic Sciences—more than any other university—and has been awarded six John Bates Clark Medals.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Not all members of the department belong to the Chicago school of economics, which is a school of thought rather than an organization.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The term was coined in the 1950s to refer to economists teaching in the Economics Department at the University of Chicago, and closely related academic areas at the university such as the Booth School of Business, Harris School of Public Policy and the Law School.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] In the context of macroeconomics, it is connected to the freshwater school of macroeconomics, in contrast to the saltwater school based in coastal universities (notably Harvard, Yale, Penn, UC Berkeley, and UCLA).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The Chicago economists met together in frequent intense discussions that helped set a group outlook on economic issues, based on price theory.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The 1950s saw the height of popularity of the Keynesian school of economics, so the members of the University of Chicago were considered heterodox.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] This group had diverse interests and approaches, but Knight, Simons, and Director in particular advocated a focus on the role of incentives and the complexity of economic events rather than on general equilibrium.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Outside of Chicago, these early leaders were important influences on the Virginia school of political economy.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Nonetheless, these scholars had an important influence on the thought of Milton Friedman and George Stigler who were the leaders of the *second-generation* Chicago school, most notably in the development of price theory and transaction cost economics.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The *third generation* of Chicago economics is led by Gary Becker, as well as macroeconomists Robert Lucas Jr. and Eugene Fama.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] A further significant branching of Chicago thought was dubbed by George Stigler as "Chicago political economy".
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Inspired by the Coasian view that institutions evolve to maximize the Pareto efficiency, Chicago political economy came to the surprising and controversial view that politics tends towards efficiency and that policy advice is irrelevant.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] As of 2022, the University of Chicago Economics Department has been awarded 15 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences (laureates were affiliated with the department when receiving the prizes) since the prize was first awarded in 1969.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] In addition, as of October 2018, 32 out of the total 81 Nobel laureates in Economics have been affiliated with the university as alumni, faculty members or researchers, which has been a source of controversy.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] However, not all members of the department belong to the Chicago school of economics.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] As of 2019, the University of Chicago Economics Department has been awarded six John Bates Clark Medals (medalists were affiliated with the department when receiving the medals) since the medal was first awarded in 1947.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] However, some medalists may *not* belong to the Chicago school of economics.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Frank Knight (1885–1972) was an early member of the University of Chicago department.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He joined the department in 1929, coming from the University of Iowa.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] His most influential work was *Risk, Uncertainty and Profit* (1921) from which the term Knightian uncertainty was derived.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Knight's perspective was iconoclastic, and markedly different from later Chicago school thinkers.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He believed that while the free market could be inefficient, government programs were even less efficient.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He drew from other economic schools of thought such as institutional economics to form his own nuanced perspective.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Henry Calvert Simons (1899–1946) did his graduate work at the University of Chicago but did not submit his final dissertation to receive a degree.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] In fact, he was initially influenced by Frank Knight while he was an assistant professor at the University of Iowa from 1925 to 1927, and in summer 1927 Simons decided to join the Department of Economics at the University of Chicago (earlier than Knight did).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He was a long-term member in the Chicago economics department, most notable for his antitrust and monetarist models.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Jacob Viner (1892–1970) was in the faculty of Chicago's economics department for 30 years (1916–1946).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He inspired a generation of economists at Chicago, including Milton Friedman.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Aaron Director (1901–2004) had been a professor at Chicago's Law School since 1946.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He is regarded as a founder of the field Law and economics and established *The Journal of Law & Economics* in 1958*.* Director influenced some of the next generation of jurists, including Richard Posner, Antonin Scalia and Chief Justice William Rehnquist.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] A group of agricultural economists led by Theodore Schultz (1902–1998) and D.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Gale Johnson (1916–2003) moved from Iowa State to the University of Chicago in the mid-1940s.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Schultz served as the chair of economics from 1946 to 1961.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He became president of the American Economic Association in 1960, retired in 1967, though he remained active at the University of Chicago until his death in 1998.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Johnson served as department chair from 1971 to 1975 and 1980–1984 and was president of the American Economics Association in 1999.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Their research in farm and agricultural economics was widely influential and attracted funding from the Rockefeller Foundation to the agricultural economics program at the university.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Among the graduate students and faculty affiliated with the pair in the 1940s and 1950s were Clifford Hardin, Zvi Griliches, Marc Nerlove, and George S.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] In 1979, Schultz was awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics for his work in human capital theory and economic development.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Milton Friedman (1912–2006) stands as one of the most influential economists of the late twentieth century.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] A student of Frank Knight, he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics in 1976 for, among other things, *A Monetary History of the United States* (1963).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Friedman argued that the Great Depression had been caused by the Federal Reserve's policies through the 1920s and worsened in the 1930s.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Governments should aim for a neutral monetary policy oriented toward long-run economic growth, by gradual expansion of the money supply.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He advocated the quantity theory of money, that general prices are determined by money.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Therefore, active monetary (e.g. easy credit) or fiscal (e.g. tax and spend) policy can have unintended negative effects.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The slogan that "money matters" has come to be associated with Friedman, but Friedman had also leveled harsh criticism of his ideological opponents.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] George Stigler (1911–1991) was tutored for his thesis by Frank Knight and was awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics in 1982.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He is best known for developing the *Economic Theory of Regulation*, also known as regulatory capture, which says that interest groups and other political participants will use the regulatory and coercive powers of government to shape laws and regulations in a way that is beneficial to them.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] This theory is an important component of the Public Choice field of economics.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He also carried out extensive research into the history of economic thought.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] His 1962 article "Information in the Labor Market" developed the theory of search unemployment.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Ronald Coase (1910–2013) was the most prominent economic analyst of law and the 1991 Nobel Prize-winner.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] His first major article, "The Nature of the Firm" (1937), argued that the reason for the existence of firms (companies, partnerships, etc.) is the existence of transaction costs.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Rational individuals trade through bilateral contracts on open markets until the costs of transactions mean that using corporations to produce things is more cost-effective.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] His second major article, "The Problem of Social Cost" (1960), argued that if we lived in a world without transaction costs, people would bargain with one another to create the same allocation of resources, regardless of the way a court might rule in property disputes.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Coase used the example of an 1879 London legal case about nuisance named *Sturges v Bridgman*, in which a noisy sweetmaker and a quiet doctor were neighbours; the doctor went to court seeking an injunction against the noise produced by the sweetmaker.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Coase said that regardless of whether the judge ruled that the sweetmaker had to stop using his machinery, or that the doctor had to put up with it, they could strike a mutually beneficial bargain that reaches the same outcome of resource distribution.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Only the existence of transaction costs may prevent this.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] So, the law ought to pre-empt what *would* happen, and be guided by the most efficient solution.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The idea is that law and regulation are not as important or effective at helping people as lawyers and government planners believe.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Coase and others like him wanted a change of approach, to put the burden of proof for positive effects on a government that was intervening in the market, by analysing the costs of action.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Gary Becker (1930–2014) received the Nobel Prize in Economics 1992 and the Presidential Medal of Freedom in 2007.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Becker received his PhD at the University of Chicago in 1955 under H.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Gregg Lewis, and was influenced by Milton Friedman.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] In 1970, he returned to Chicago as a professor and stayed affiliated with the university until his death.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He is considered one of the founding fathers of Chicago political economy, and one of the most influential economists and social scientists in the second half of the twentieth century.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Becker was known in his work for applying economic methods of thinking to other fields, such as crime, sexual relationships, slavery and drugs, assuming that people act rationally.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] His work was originally focused in labor economics.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] His work partly inspired the popular economics book *Freakonomics*.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] In June 2011, the Becker Friedman Institute for Research in Economics was established at the University of Chicago in honor of Gary Becker and Milton Friedman.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Robert Lucas (born 1937), who won the Nobel Prize in 1995, has dedicated his life to unwinding Keynesianism.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] His major contribution is the argument that macroeconomics should not be seen as a separate mode of thought from microeconomics, and that analysis in both should be built on the same foundations.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Lucas's works cover several topics in macroeconomics, included economic growth, asset pricing, and monetary economics.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Eugene Fama (born 1939) is an American financial economist who was awarded the Nobel Prize in Economics in 2013 for his work on empirical asset pricing and is the fourth most highly cited economist of all time.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He has spent all of his teaching career at the University of Chicago and is the originator of the efficient-market hypothesis, first defined in his 1965 article as a market where "at any point in time, the actual price of a security will be a good estimate of its intrinsic value".
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The notion was further explored in his 1970 article, "Efficient Capital Markets: A Review of Theory and Empirical Work", which brought the notion of efficient markets into the forefront of modern economic theory, and his 1991 article, "Efficient Markets II".
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] His work showing that the value premium can persist despite rational forecasts of future earnings and that the performance of actively managed funds is almost entirely due to chance or exposure to risk are all supportive of an efficient-markets view of the world.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Robert Fogel (1926–2013), a co-winner of the Nobel Prize in 1993, is well known for his historical analysis and his introduction of New economic history, and invention of cliometrics.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] In his tract, *Railroads and American Economic Growth: Essays in Econometric History,* Fogel set out to rebut comprehensively the idea that railroads contributed to economic growth in the 19th century.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Later, in *Time on the Cross: The Economics of American Negro Slavery*, he argued that slaves in the Southern states of America had a higher standard of living than the industrial proletariat of the Northern states before the American Civil War.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] James Heckman (born 1944) is a Nobel Prize-winner from 2000, is known for his pioneering work in econometrics and microeconomics.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Lars Peter Hansen (born 1952) is an American economist who won the Nobel Prize in Economics in 2013 with Eugene Fama and Robert Shiller for their work on asset pricing.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Hansen began teaching at the University of Chicago in 1981 and is the David Rockefeller Distinguished Service Professor of economics at the University of Chicago.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Although best known for his work on the Generalized method of moments, he is also a distinguished macroeconomist, focusing on the linkages between the financial and real sectors of the economy.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Richard Posner (born 1939) is known primarily for his work in law and economics, though Robert Solow describes Posner's grasp of certain economic ideas as "in some respects,... precarious".
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] A federal appellate judge rather than an economist, Posner's main work, *Economic Analysis of Law* attempts to apply rational choice models to areas of law.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He has chapters on tort, contract, corporations, labor law, but also criminal law, discrimination and family law.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Friedrich Hayek (1899–1992) made frequent contacts with many at the University of Chicago during the 1940s, while he was still at the London School of Economics (he moved to the University of Chicago in 1950).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] His book *The Road to Serfdom,* published in the U.S. by the University of Chicago Press in September 1944 with the help of Aaron Director, played a seminal role in transforming how Milton Friedman and others understood how society works.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The University Press continued to publish a large number of Hayek's works in later years, such as *The Fatal Conceit* and *The Constitution of Liberty*.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] In 1947, Hayek, Frank Knight, Friedman and George Stigler worked together in forming the Mont Pèlerin Society, an international forum for libertarian economists.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] During 1950–1962, Hayek was a faculty member of the Committee of Social Thought at the University of Chicago, where he conducted a number of influential faculty seminars.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] There were a number of Chicago academics who worked on research projects sympathetic to some of Hayek's own, such as Aaron Director, who was active in the Chicago School in helping to fund and establish what became the "Law and Society" program in the University of Chicago Law School.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Hayek and Friedman also cooperated in support of the Intercollegiate Society of Individualists, later renamed the Intercollegiate Studies Institute, an American student organisation devoted to libertarian ideas.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Buchanan (1919–2013) won the 1986 Nobel Prize in Economics for his public choice theory.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Knight at the University of Chicago, receiving PhD in 1948.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Although he did not hold any position at the university afterwards, his later work is closely related to the thought of the Chicago school.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Buchanan was the foremost proponent of the Virginia school of political economy.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Thomas Sowell (born in 1930) received his PhD at the University of Chicago in 1968, under George Stigler.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] A libertarian conservative in his perspective, he is considered to be a representative of the Chicago school.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] Paul Douglas, economist and Democratic senator from Illinois for 18 years, was uncomfortable with the environment he found at the university.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] He stated that, "...I was disconcerted to find that the economic and political conservatives had acquired almost complete dominance over my department and taught that market decisions were always right and profit values the supreme ones...
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] The opinions of my colleagues would have confined government to the eighteenth-century functions of justice, police, and arms, which I thought had been insufficient even for that time and were certainly so for ours.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] These men would neither use statistical data to develop economic theory nor accept critical analysis of the economic system...
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] (Frank) Knight was now openly hostile, and his disciples seemed to be everywhere.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] While the efficacy of Eugene Fama's efficient-market hypothesis (EMH) was debated after the 2008 financial crisis, proponents emphasized that the EMH is consistent with the large decline in asset prices since the event was unpredictable.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/chicago-school-of-economics] A film titled *Chicago Boys*, which had a highly critical view of the economic reforms, was released in Chile in November 2015.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] In economics, a **complementary good** is a good whose appeal increases with the popularity of another good, which is known as its *complement*.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Technically, it displays a negative cross elasticity of demand and that demand for it increases when the price of another good decreases.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] If A is a complement to B , an increase in the price of A will result in a negative movement along the demand curve of A and cause the demand curve for B to shift inward; less of each good will be demanded.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Conversely, a decrease in the price of A will result in a positive movement along the demand curve of A and cause the demand curve of B to shift outward; more of each good will be demanded.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] This is in contrast to a substitute good, whose demand decreases when its substitute's price decreases.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] When two goods are complements, they experience *joint demand* - the demand of one good is linked to the demand for another good.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Therefore, if a higher quantity is demanded of one good, a higher quantity will also be demanded of the other, and *vice versa*.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] For example, the demand for razor blades may depend on the number of razors in use; this is why razors have sometimes been sold as loss leaders, to increase demand for the associated blades.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Another example is that sometimes a toothbrush is packaged free with toothpaste.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] The toothbrush is a complement to the toothpaste; the cost of producing a toothbrush may be higher than toothpaste, but its sales depends on the demand of toothpaste.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] All non-complementary goods can be considered substitutes.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] If x and y are rough complements in an everyday sense, then consumers are willing to pay more for each marginal unit of good x as they accumulate more y .
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] The opposite is true for substitutes: the consumer is willing to pay less for each marginal unit of good " z " as it accumulates more of good " y ".
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Complementarity may be driven by psychological processes in which the consumption of one good (e.g., cola) stimulates demand for its complements (e.g., a cheeseburger).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Consumption of a food or beverage activates a goal to consume its complements: foods that consumers believe would taste better together.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Drinking cola increases consumers' willingness to pay for a cheeseburger.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] This effect appears to be contingent on consumer perceptions of these relationships rather than their sensory properties.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] An example of this would be the demand for cars and petrol.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] The supply and demand for cars is represented by the figure, with the initial demand $D_{1}$ .
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Suppose that the initial price of cars is represented by $P_{1}$ with a quantity demanded of $Q_{1}$ .
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] If the price of petrol were to decrease by some amount, this would result in a higher quantity of cars demanded.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] This higher quantity demanded would cause the demand curve to shift rightward to a new position $D_{2}$ .
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Assuming a constant supply curve S of cars, the new increased quantity demanded will be at $Q_{2}$ with a new increased price $P_{2}$ .
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Other examples include automobiles and fuel, mobile phones and cellular service, printer and cartridge, among others.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] A *perfect complement* is a good that *must* be consumed with another good.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] The indifference curve of a perfect complement exhibits a right angle, as illustrated by the figure.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Such preferences can be represented by a Leontief utility function.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Few goods behave as perfect complements.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] One example is a left shoe and a right; shoes are naturally sold in pairs, and the ratio between sales of left and right shoes will never shift noticeably from 1:1.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] The degree of complementarity, however, does not have to be mutual; it can be measured by the cross price elasticity of demand.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] In the case of video games, a specific video game (the complement good) has to be consumed with a video game console (the base good).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] It does not work the other way: a video game console does not have to be consumed with that game.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] In marketing, complementary goods give additional market power to the producer.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] It allows vendor lock-in by increasing switching costs.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Sometimes the complement-relationship between two goods is not intuitive and must be verified by inspecting the cross-elasticity of demand using market data.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] The elasticity does not need to be symmetrical.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] Thus, y is a gross complement of x while x can simultaneously be a gross substitutes for y .
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] If x is a gross substitute for y , the left-hand side of the equation and the first term of right-hand side are positive.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] By the symmetry of Mosak's perspective, evaluating the equation with respect to $x^{*}$ , the first term of right-hand side stays the same while some extreme cases exist where $x^{*}$ is large enough to make the whole right-hand-side negative.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/complementary-good] In this case, y is a gross complement of x .
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] Consumables are products that consumers use *recurrently*, i.e., items which "get used up" or discarded.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] For example, consumable office supplies are such products as paper, pens, file folders, Post-it notes, and toner or ink cartridges.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] This is in contrast to capital goods or durable goods in the office, such as computers, fax machines, and other business machines or office furniture.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] Sometimes a company sells a durable good at an attractively low price in the hopes that the consumer will then buy the consumables that go with it at a price providing a higher margin.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] Printers and ink cartridges are an example, as are cameras and film as well as razors and blades, which gave this business model its usual name (the razor and blades model).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] Printing consumables include items like toner cartridges, which are consumed, utilized and then exhausted.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] These supplies are considered to be a major element of printing process.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] For arc welding one uses a *consumable* electrode.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] This is an electrode that conducts electricity to the arc but also melts into the weld as a filler metal.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] Consumable goods are often excluded from warranty policies, as it is considered that covering them would excessively increase the cost of the premium.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] They are also known as **consumable goods**, **non-durable goods**, or **soft goods**.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] The "razor and blades business model" is a business model in which one item is sold at a low price (or given away) in order to increase sales of a complementary good, such as consumable supplies.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] While the model is named after razors, it applies to any business model using a durable item that needs consumable parts.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] It is different from loss leader marketing and product sample marketing, which do not depend on complementary products or services.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/consumables] Although the concept and the catchphrase "Give 'em the razor; sell 'em the blades" are widely credited to King Camp Gillette, the inventor of the safety razor, Gillette did not in fact follow this model.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] In economics, a **durable good** or a **hard good** or **consumer durable** is a good that does not quickly wear out or, more specifically, one that yields utility over time rather than being completely consumed in one use.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Items like bricks could be considered perfectly durable goods because they should theoretically never wear out.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Highly durable goods such as refrigerators or cars usually continue to be useful for several years of use, so durable goods are typically characterized by long periods between successive purchases.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Durable goods are typically replaced due to obsolescence rather than breakdown.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Durable goods are known to form an imperative part of economic production.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] This can be exemplified from the fact that personal expenditures on durables exceeded the total value of $800 billion in 2000.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] In the year 2000 itself, durable goods production composed of approximately 60 percent of aggregate production within the manufacturing sector in the United States.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Examples of consumer durable goods include housing, vehicles, books, household goods (home appliances, consumer electronics, furniture, musical instruments, tools, etc.), sports equipment, jewelry, medical equipment, and toys.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Durability can be defined "the ability of a product to perform its required function over a lengthy period under normal conditions of use without excessive expenditure on maintenance or repair".
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Several units may be used to measure the durability of a product according to its field of application such as years of existence, hours of use and operational cycles.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] The life span of household goods is significant for sustainable consumption.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] The longer product life spans could contribute to eco-efficiency and sufficiency, thus slowing consumption in order to progress towards a sustainable consumption.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Cooper (2005) proposed a model to demonstrate the crucial role of product life spans for sustainable production and consumption.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Durability, as a characteristic relating to the quality of goods that can be demanded by consumers, was not clear until an amendment of the law in 1994 relating to the quality standards for supplied goods.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] The condition of the economy is one of the biggest factors as well as the philosophy of money.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Consumers want to use their money effectively and essentially get what they paid for, and in the best-case scenario, get more than what they paid for.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] In the pursuit of durable goods through the lifespans of the products and consumption of those products money and price dictate two of the biggest factors other than supply and demand.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/durable-good] Durable goods fall into this category, as ease of commerce and convenience are key factors in making it a good product to buy.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Since 1975, Kodak had followed a policy of selling patented and unpatented repair parts only to direct purchasers of its equipment.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The 18 plaintiffs in this case are Independent Service Organizations ("ISOs") engaged in repairing and servicing Kodak's copiers and other equipment, and in buying, reconditioning and selling used Kodak copiers and equipment.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The effect of these practices is to bar sales of parts required to repair and maintain Kodak copiers and imaging equipment to the ISOs.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] In addition, Kodak refuses to sell maintenance service contracts on used equipment unless it is first inspected and brought up to standard by Kodak.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Therefore, purchasers of used equipment from ISOs who want to purchase a maintenance agreement for the equipment from Kodak must first submit the equipment to Kodak for inspection and any necessary repair and upgrading.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The ISOs sued Kodak, alleging that it violated Sections 1 and 2 of the Sherman Act, 15 U.S.C. §§ 1, 2, and Section 3 of the Clayton Act, 15 U.S.C. § 14.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The district court granted Kodak's motion for summary judgment and dismissed the complaint.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The court turned to the section 2 monopolization claim.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The ISOs contended that Kodak monopolized by leveraging monopoly power in one market to gain competitive advantage in another.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The court rejected this argument as lacking any factual support.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak competes as an OEM with Xerox, IBM, Bell and Howell, 3M, and various Japanese manufacturers and has no significant market share as an OEM.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The district court dismissed the complaint and the ISOs appealed to the Ninth Circuit.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Ninth Circuit reversed the summary judgment, 2–1.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Preliminarily, the Ninth Circuit characterized at least one of the issues somewhat differently from the district court—as involving concerted rather than unilateral action.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Ninth Circuit said there were two main issues: "First, Kodak will not sell replacement parts for its equipment to Kodak equipment owners unless they agree not to use ISOs.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Ninth Circuit also emphasized some facts to which the district court had not referred.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] After 1982 ISOs began to compete significantly against Kodak in the repair of Kodak equipment.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] ISOs offered service for as little as half of Kodak's price.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] To better compete, Kodak in some cases cut its price for service.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Some customers found ISO service superior to Kodak service.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak then developed its present policies of not selling replacement parts to ISOs or to customers who use ISOs.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] As to the Section 1 issue, Kodak and the district court misconceived the statute.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak argued that it does not force owners to buy service in order to receive parts; Kodak only requires owners *not to buy ISO service* to receive parts.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak will sell parts to owners who agree to self-service their machines.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Ninth Circuit said that an unlawful tie-in violation occurs not only when a seller conditions a sale of one thing on the purchase of another thing too.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] It is also a violation to get the purchaser to agree not to purchase things from another seller.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] That raised the question whether, if there was a tie-in, did Kodak have the market power necessary to make the tie unlawful.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The ISOs argued that Kodak does have power in the parts market for two interdependent reasons.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] First, many Kodak parts are unique and available only from Kodak.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Second, owners of Kodak machinery cannot readily switch to other companies' machinery (thereby obviating the need for Kodak parts).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Once one owns Kodak's expensive machinery, he is locked in to it.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak countered that it had no power in the primary market, because its market share relative to IBM, Xerox, 3M, and the others was small.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] If equipment buyers find Kodak charging too much for parts and services, they will buy from IBM, Xerox, 3M, etc. instead of from Kodak.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] But once a purchaser has bought a Kodak copier, he cannot turn to IBM or Xerox for parts to fix his broken Kodak copier.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] A price differential is evidence of market power.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] This indicates that there is a material issue of fact over market power, and therefore summary judgment on the issue was improvident.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak argued that it acted unilaterally in refusing to deal with the ISOs.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Turning to the monopolization claim, the Ninth Circuit concluded that there were material issues of fact concerning whether Kodak fell within one of the exceptions to the principle that a firm generally has no duty to deal with competitors.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] On the factual record before the court, it was not possible to determine that summary judgment was proper.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Therefore, the issue would have to be tried in the district court.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Justice Blackmun delivered the opinion of the Court, in which Chief Justice Rehnquist and Justices White, Stevens, Kennedy and Souter joined.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Justice Scalia filed a dissenting opinion, in which Justices O'Connor and Thomas joined.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Supreme Court affirmed the Ninth Circuit's denial of Kodak's summary judgment motion reversing the district court.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Justice Blackmun began by emphasizing some additional facts from the record that neither court below had relied on.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak did not make all of the parts that went into its equipment.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] It purchased parts from parts manufacturers.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak also pressured Kodak equipment owners and independent parts distributors not to sell Kodak parts to ISOs.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] In addition, Kodak took steps to restrict the availability to ISOs of used machines.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak intended to and was successful, through these policies, in making it more difficult for ISOs to sell service for Kodak machines.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] ISOs were unable to obtain parts from reliable sources, and many were forced out of business, while others lost substantial revenue.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Customers were forced to switch to Kodak service even though they preferred ISO service.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] It insisted that this was a fact issue, not something to be decided by theory.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak was equally insistent that the existence of market power in the service and parts markets, absent power in the equipment market, "simply makes no economic sense," and the absence of a legal presumption would deter procompetitive behavior.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Court then turned to the final issue: whether there were genuine issues for trial as to whether Kodak has monopolized, or attempted to monopolize, the Kodak equipment service and parts markets, in violation of § 2 of the Sherman Act.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Court said that the evidence that Kodak controls nearly 100% of the parts market and 80% to 95% of the service market, with no readily available substitutes, was sufficient to survive summary judgment under the stringent monopoly standard of § 2.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak contended, however, that as a matter of law a single brand of a product or service can never be a relevant market under the Sherman Act.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Summary judgment is therefore inappropriate.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Justice Scalia dissented and denied that this was just another case on the proper standard for summary judgment, as the majority had said.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] A "rational consumer considering the purchase of Kodak equipment will inevitably factor into his purchasing decision the expected cost of aftermarket support." Therefore, Kodak could not logically have market power in a supposed relevant market for unique Kodak parts.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] To be sure, there are some irrational consumers, such as the U.S.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Government, "[b]ut we have never before premised the application of antitrust doctrine on the lowest common denominator of consumer.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] As for monopolization under § 2, it should be reserved as "a specialized mechanism for responding to extraordinary agglomerations (or threatened agglomerations) of economic power," not mere power over one's one brand of product where there exists a vibrant interbrand market.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] In August 1997 the Ninth Circuit considered the case another time on remand.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The court affirmed a jury verdict that awarded the ISOs $72 million in treble damages on section 2 of the Sherman Act.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] It also allowed a 10-year injunction that requiring Kodak to sell the parts for its machines at reasonable, non-monopoly and nondiscriminatory prices.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The ISOs contended that Kodak had used its monopoly in the parts market to monopolize, or attempt to monopolize, the service market.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak now asserted that its intellectual property rights provided a defense against the claim.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The court held that rights under patents and copyrights are a rebuttably presumed legitimate business justification for refusing to deal with competitors.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] However, the ISOs rebutted the presumption.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] In addition to possessing its market share, Kodak engaged in exclusionary conduct.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] That left the main issue whether the patent ownership justified what would otherwise be monopolization.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Ninth Circuit said the case presented a question of first impression.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] "At the border of intellectual property monopolies and antitrust markets lies a field of dissonance yet to be harmonized by statute or the Supreme Court." Some weight, but not decisive weight, must be given to the intellectual property rights of a monopolist.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] This presumption could be rebutted if the justifications for invoking intellectual property rights were merely pretextual and just an excuse for exclusionary conduct.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The injunction requiring part sales originally applied to all parts.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Ninth Circuit limited the injunction to parts made by Kodak, since the ISOs could now buy such parts from their independent manufacturers.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Kodak argued that on parts for which it had a copyright or patent monopoly, it should be allowed to charge monopoly prices rather than merely "reasonable" prices.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The Ninth Circuit said when compulsory sales relief was ordered in patent-antitrust cases, the courts ordered the sales to be a "reasonable" prices.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] In this case, however, it would be sufficient that the prices be nondiscriminatory and therefore the Ninth Circuit modified the district court's injunction order to eliminate the reasonableness requirement.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Herbert Hovenkamp has been highly critical of the decision.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] In his 2006 book *The Antitrust Enterprise*, he strongly disagreed that a single-brand aftermarket could ever constitute a separate relevant market.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Mark Patterson argues in the *North Carolina Law Review* that the *Kodak* decision is rational and economically sound, incorporating into antitrust law previously neglected but important economic learning about the cost and value of product information and its relevance to creating market power.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] He points to other cases in the past where market power was created by making information expensive to obtain.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] For example, in *National Society of Professional Engineers v.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] United States*, the Supreme Court held illegal an engineering society's rule that forbade members from providing price information to buyers until the buyers had tentatively agreed to purchase the members' services.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Patterson gives as another example *FTC v.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Indiana Federation of Dentists*, in which the Supreme Court held it illegal for a dentists' organization to establish a policy requiring its members to withhold x-rays from dental insurers in connection with evaluating claims for benefits.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Eleanor Fox perceives *Kodak* as "essentially a case about abusing competitors; it is not essentially a case about lack of consumer information," as many other analysts perceive it.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] A paper by three economists—Borenstein, MacKie-Mason, and Netz—agrees with the *Kodak* Court that "market imperfections can keep economic theories about how consumers will react from mirroring reality." But they argue that the Court did not go far enough in rejecting the defense economic arguments.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] In a declining market for original equipment, which many antitrust cases have involved, there is a great incentive to charge high aftermarket prices at the expense of incumbent equipment owners.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Even if equipment demand is expected to remain constant, the writers argue, profits in the future are of less value due to discounting.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The authors then address other information costs.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] They explain that, even if there were no switching costs to adopting a new brand, high aftermarket prices would still be rational.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The reason is that a manufacturer's aftermarket pricing policies can raise the cost of switching by lowering the market value of a customer's used equipment.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] When a customer switches it pays the net cost of the new brand of equipment minus the used value of its old brand of equipment.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] A manufacturer's increase in service or parts prices will correspondingly lower the market value of used equipment.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] A Comment by Jill Protos in the *Case Western Reserve Law Review* perceives the decision of the Supreme Court as a setback for the Chicago Law School's form of antitrust analysis.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] In addition, the model does not consider switching costs and resulting lock-in.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] In a Comment in the *Notre Dame Law Review*, Lawrence Fesca also sees the *Kodak* decision as a setback for the Chicago School, but finds it less distressing, and also he considers seeing the decision as an announcement of Chicago demise to be an exaggeration.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] But the Note faults the Ninth Circuit's analysis because it "does not harmonize this 'field of dissonance' directly."That is, the court did not decide whether the scope of the patent rights *should* have extended to the use of parts to provide service and maintenance.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Reliance on pretext to condemn the restraints is too case–specific.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] It fails to "offer much insight or guidance as to how this court will, or any other court should, review firms' actions" in future cases.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] Relying on the Supreme Court's 1908 decision in *Continental Paper Bag Co. v.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The author considers high-tech industries that evolve and change rapidly and are complicated.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] That may call for different rules than used in the past.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] His focus is on selective refusals to deal used to require adherence to a restrictive practice.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The author then turned to the two cases involving Intel.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] As in *Xerox*, the Federal Circuit in *Intergraph* found IP rights dominant, and it simply rejected the Ninth Circuit's view in the *Kodak* remand case.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] The FTC acted against Intel, however, because it saw unlawful monopolization in Intel's refusal to deal (provide technical information on purchased microprocessor chips or sell chips) unless customers were willing to make their patents available to Intel.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/eastman-kodak-co-v-image-technical-services-inc] unless the patentee proffers a valid reason to justify its refusal.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The installed base plays a significant role in various industries, including computing, automotive, medical devices, and home appliances.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] It can impact the level of support, availability of replacement parts, and other factors.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Some companies that have leveraged their installed base include Apple, Microsoft, Nintendo in the computing industry, and Tesla in the automotive industry.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The installed base of company's products represents a valuable customer base that is already using their products, services or systems.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] This provides companies with an opportunity to upsell and cross-sell their products to existing customers, as well as to use the information about their customer base to inform future product development and marketing efforts.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Companies can use their installed base to determine the average lifespan of their products, which can inform product development and planning, as well as to assess their market position and to track the success of their product over time.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The size of a company's installed base reflects the number of products, systems, or services currently in use by customers.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] This can be used as a measure of a company's market position and customer base.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The composition of an installed base can be evaluated to determine the types of products, systems or services in use, and the demographics of the customers using them.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] This information can be used to inform product development, marketing, and sales efforts.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The lifespan of products in the installed base can provide important information about the average lifespan of a company's products and systems.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] This information can be used to inform product development and planning.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The geographic location of customers using a company's products, systems or services can be used to inform sales and marketing efforts.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The rate at which customers upgrade or replace products in the installed base can provide important information about the success of a company's product and the willingness of customers to invest in new or upgraded versions.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The installed base of computer systems, such as operating systems and video game consoles/platforms, is a significant factor in their respective industries.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] In these markets, the size of the installed base is a key indicator of the reach and influence of a particular product or platform.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Installed base is also a significant factor in other industries, such as automotive, medical devices, and home appliances.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] In these markets, the size of the installed base of a particular product or platform can impact the level of support and availability of replacement parts and accessories.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The installed base is used to determine the size and growth potential of a particular market.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Manufacturers use the installed base information to plan the development of new products and services, and to determine the potential for future sales.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Service providers use the installed base information to determine the level of support required for a particular product or service, and to allocate resources accordingly.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Sales teams use the installed base information to make informed decisions about sales targets and to allocate resources accordingly.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Manufacturers and service providers use the installed base information to determine the optimal price for their products and services, taking into account the size of the market and the competition.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Apple's installed base of iOS devices, such as the iPhone and iPad, has allowed the company to offer a wide variety of accessories and services.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Apple's app store and media offerings are tailored to its device ecosystem, providing customers with a seamless experience.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Microsoft's installed base of Windows operating systems has provided the company with a platform to offer a diverse array of software and services.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Its suite of productivity tools, including Microsoft Office, are designed to be used with Windows computers.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Nintendo has a large installed base of its video game consoles, which it leverages to sell more games and accessories.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] For example, the company has a suite of video game series, such as Mario and Zelda, that are designed to work best on Nintendo consoles.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] Tesla's installed base of electric vehicles provides the company with an opportunity to offer related products and services, such as charging stations and energy storage systems.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/installed-base] The company has also leveraged the data generated by its vehicles to improve its self-driving technology.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] A **loss leader** (also **leader**) is a product is sold at a price below its minimum profit margin to stimulate other sales of more profitable goods or services.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The use of a loss leader is a pricing strategy, a sales promotion strategy, and a marketing strategy.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The loss leader is offered at a price below its minimum profit margin, not necessarily below cost.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] One use of a loss leader is to draw customers into a store where they are likely to buy other goods.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The vendor expects that the typical customer will purchase other goods at the same time as the loss leader and that the profit made on these goods will be such that an overall profit is generated for the vendor.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The vendor tries to maintain a current analysis of its accounts for both the loss leader and the associated goods, so it can monitor how well the scheme is doing to avoid an overall net loss.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] It is called a *leader* because it is intended to *lead* to the subsequent sale of other goods or services.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Marketing academics have shown that retailers should think of both the direct and indirect effect of substantial price promotions when evaluating their impact on profit.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] To make a very precise analysis one should also include effects over time.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Deep price promotions may cause people to bulk-buy (stockpile), which may invalidate the long-term effect of the strategy.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] When automobile dealerships in the United States use this practice, they offer at least one vehicle below cost and must disclose all of the features of the vehicle (including the VIN).
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] If the loss-leader vehicle has been sold, the salesperson tries to sell a more upscale trim of that vehicle at a slightly discounted price, as a customer who has missed the loss-leading vehicle is unlikely to find a better deal elsewhere.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Loss leaders can be an important part of companies' marketing and sales strategies, especially during "dumping" campaigns.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Some examples of typical loss leaders include milk, eggs, rice, and other inexpensive items that grocers would not want to sell without the customer making other purchases.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] While some customers may have the discipline to only buy the loss leaders, the loss leader strategy works because a customer who goes into a grocery store to buy an inexpensive bread or milk item may decide to buy other grocery items.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The *Warner/Reprise Loss Leaders* were a series of promotional sampler compilation albums released by Warner Bros.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Warner advertised the Loss Leaders albums by inserting special illustrated inner sleeves in all of its regular album releases, listing all of the currently available Loss Leaders and including an order form.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Each loss leader double album was priced at US$2, significantly less than a comparable regular-release double album of the time.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The first Loss Leaders compilation was *The 1969 Warner/Reprise Songbook*, featuring a wide range of artists from Miriam Makeba to The Mothers of Invention; the last of the original series was the punk and new wave-themed *Troublemakers* in 1980.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] In 1979, American businessman Earl Muntz decided to sell blank tapes and VCRs as loss leaders to attract customers to his showroom, where he would then try to sell them highly profitable widescreen projection TV systems of his own design.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] His success continued through the early 1980s.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] On its launch in 1959 the British Motor Corporation's Mini car was sold at a starting price (including taxes) of £496 for its most basic model, and it was estimated that BMC lost £30 per car sold at this price.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The ploy did not work entirely as BMC intended—even in its most basic form, the Mini was far superior in many areas to its rivals while also being lower in price.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] BMC sold far more basic Minis than it had anticipated, meaning that it sold many Minis at a significant loss.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Despite the car being a bestseller in Britain (and several other markets) it made little to no profit for many years.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Supermarkets sell food staples such as bananas or milk at less than the cost at which they were purchased in order to draw customers to their business.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] These items are typically strategically placed far from the entrances of the store to enhance this effect.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] In the case of milk, supermarket chains often refuse to pay market rates to avoid making a loss.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Costco sells its quarter-pound hotdog and soda combo for $1.50 USD, a price point that has not changed since 1985 and is believed to be well below cost, to bring customers into the store.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] It also sells its rotisserie chicken well below cost, at $4.99.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The $1.50 price point is both famous and popular among Costco customers.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] For example, a 2018 Seattle business magazine story disclosing that co-founder and former CEO James Sinegal cursed out then-CEO W.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Craig Jelinek in 2013 for merely thinking about raising the price of the Costco hot dog was the most viral story ever run by that publisher as of 2024.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Supermarkets in the UK including Tesco, Asda, Sainsburys and Morrisons have engaged in an annual loss leader price war for Christmas vegetables since discounters Aldi and Lidl gained market share.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Christmas staple items such as carrots, cabbage and sprouts are priced as low as 8p per kilogram - well below the price the businesses pay to farmers and the usual RRP of around 70p.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The tactic intends for customers to pick up the cheap vegetables and then do a full shop that includes highly profitable Christmas items such as desserts, Christmas crackers and decorations.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] There is some concern that this intense price war hurts farmers.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Many toy store chains and online retailers sell diapers or nappies as a loss leader in order to entice parents into the store in the hopes that the children will spot toys, bottles or other items that the family desires.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Large hardware stores often sell larger tools, such as drills or electric saws at cost or below.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] They do this expecting customers to buy accessories such as blades, drill bits, stands, or cases, along with the new tool.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] These items tend to have a much higher profit margin, and are often impulse buys.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Some consumer electronics stores use smartphones and other mobile electronics as loss leaders.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The company makes less profit on smartphone or mobile devices, but it makes up for this through the sales of higher-profit accessories such as cases, headphones and power adapters.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Gaming consoles, such as the Xbox 360/PlayStation 3, Xbox One/PlayStation 4, or Xbox Series X/S/PlayStation 5, are often initially sold as loss leaders.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] This helps assert market share for the console, which enables the creation of a development ecosystem for games.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] The profit is then made on the sale of games and accessories over the system's lifetime.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Often, printers are sold at or below manufacturing cost, drawing consumers in through low prices.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Manufacturers do so expecting the overwhelming majority of consumers to continue purchase OEM ink cartridges rather than opting for less reliable third-party products.
[src:aftermarket-merchandise/loss-leader] Profit is then recovered through cartridge sales throughout the lifetime of the printer.
